cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this software or build on the ideas, please cite both the paper and this software repository."
title: "The Deterministic Horizon: When Extended Reasoning Fails and Tool Delegation Becomes Necessary"
abstract: >
  Extended chain-of-thought reasoning can degrade performance on deterministic
  state-tracking tasks — not due to preference biases, but fundamental
  information-theoretic limits in decoder-only transformers. We establish an
  Attention Bottleneck Theorem with matching lower bound, a context-dependent
  error model yielding super-exponential accuracy decay, the State-Space
  Jaccard metric distinguishing capability from preference failures, and the
  Deterministic Horizon d* ∈ [19, 31] beyond which tool delegation becomes
  necessary. Across 12 models and 8 task domains, tool-integrated reasoning
  achieves 94% accuracy versus 28–42% for neural chain-of-thought.
